                  <abstract>
                     <p>The impact<italic>of The Tale of Genji</italic>on its first readers, and their responses to it, can be fully appreciated only within the context of the romances or tales (<italic>monogatari</italic>) they were reading before the appearance of<italic>Genji</italic>and what was being said about them, by both their devotees and their detractors. Only three prose fictions of any length survive from the century before<italic>Genji: The Tale of the Bamboo Cutter (Taketori monogatari), The Tale of the Hollow Tree (Utsuho monogatari)</italic>, and<italic>The Tale of the Lady in the Lower Room (Ochikubo monogatari)</italic>. That such tales abounded we know from</p>
                  </abstract>
