                  <fpage>158</fpage>
                  <abstract>
                     <p>That sea change in attitudes toward<italic>The Tale of Genji</italic>that we sum up under the convenient rubric of “canonization” is in fact a shifting amalgam of forces, some in concert, some in conflict, never quite coalescing in total consensus, yet yielding ultimately what one scholar aptly describes as the transformation of<italic>Genji</italic>from “a women’s romance into a men’s classic.”¹ Very little documentation of this process, which spanned at least two centuries, survives, but the scattering of sources that we do have allows us at least roughly to chart its progress. We can assume, first of all, that the</p>
