                  <abstract>
                     <p>When Japan entered the fray of global politics at the end of the nineteenth century, its new nation builders were convinced that a national literature, which presupposed a common and continuous national language, would be indispensable to the construction of a unified nationstate. In this context,<italic>The Tale of Genji</italic>was to become a crucial text.</p>
